<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-768  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 768.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 24 1989 n535 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ETA: a supercomputing Mflop. (Control Data Corp closes ETA Systemssubsidiary)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Costlow, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Control Data Corp (CDC) closes its 3,100-person ETA Systems Incsupercomputer manufacturing subsidiary and takes a $490 millionwrite off.andP;  The departure of ETA is expected to have minimummarket impact because of the low sales history.andP;  The firm soldseven of its top-end liquid-nitrogen-cooled systems, mostly toweather-tracking facilities, and 27 of the air-cooled Pipersystems; and CDC has committed to continuing their support.andP;  ETAlost $100 million in 1988 on estimated sales of $50 million to $80million.andP;  Declining cash flow and CDC's bankers forced the closureof ETA.andP;  ETA's problems in achieving profitable market presenceresulted from difficulty in porting software to the systems,relatively slow 'average' performance, insufficient applicationspackages, and poor execution of the firm's technical and businessprograms.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   ETA Systems Inc. (finance)Control Data Corp. (divestment).andO;Ticker:    CDA.andO;Topic:     LossesParent CompanySupercomputersDivestmentFailure.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Ups and downs of Control Data and supercomputing unit ETA. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>